Latest Articles







                    Making Tires From a Desert Shrub Found in the U.S.                
In seeking a domestic source for natural rubber, Cooper Tire and Rubber Company has created a way to make tires with rubber from the guayule plant, which thrives in the Southwest.
By DIANE CARDWELL













DealBook

                    Apollo Tyres Open to Transactions Despite Cooper Tire Deal Collapse                











DealBook

                    Cooper Tire Abandons Merger                
Cooper Tire & Rubber announced on Monday that it had ended its merger agreement with Apollo Tyres of India, saying that funding for the deal was no longer available.
By DAVID GELLES














                    Odds Grow for Apollo to Drop Tire Deal                
The Delaware Supreme Court has dismissed an appeal by Cooper Tire that had sought to require Apollo, of India, to complete a proposed $2.3 billion takeover of the American firm.










DealBook

                    Convoluted Language Makes Cooper Tire Deal Harder to Execute                
A judge’s ruling related to the provisions of a deal for Cooper Tire to sell itself to an Indian rival brings up an interesting debate about the language of merger agreements, the author writes.
By STEVEN DAVIDOFF SOLOMON













DealBook

                    Despite Bumps, Tire Deal Still Makes Sense                
While Cooper Tire and Rubber and Apollo Tyres, are locked in a legal battle over a $35-a-share takeover offer, the deal still has justification, even at a lower price.










DealBook

                    Escalating War of Words in Tire Deal                
Apollo Tyres indicated on Tuesday that it still wanted to acquire Cooper Tire and Rubber, but not necessarily at the agreed-on $2.5 billion price.
By DAVID GELLES













DealBook

                    A Way Out of the Cooper Tire-Apollo Tyres Mess                
The Indian tire company’s $35-a-share takeover offer for its American rival is in doubt. Yet there are plenty of avenues for a compromise, the authors contend.










DealBook

                    The Hurdles Ahead for a Cooper Tire Deal                
Labor issues are among the reasons Apollo Tyres may be having buyer’s remorse about its deal to buy Cooper Tire at $35 a share. But can Cooper force the deal to go through at that price?
By STEVEN DAVIDOFF SOLOMON













DealBook

                    More Setbacks in Deal for U.S. Tire Maker                
The proposed buyout of Cooper Tire and Rubber by Apollo Tyres has been delayed by labor opposition in two countries, and now Cooper has filed suit against its suitor.
By DAVID GELLES

















DealBook

                    Indian Tire Maker’s Shares Tumble Over Deal for Cooper                
Shares of Apollo Tyres plunged more than 25 percent in India on news of its proposed $2.5 billion acquisition of Cooper Tire and Rubber over concerns about the amount of debt it was taking on.










DealBook

                    Indian Tire Maker to Buy Cooper Tire for $2.5 Billion                
The all-cash acquisition of Cooper Tire and Rubber would give Apollo Tyres of India a major foothold in the United States.











                    Today In Business: Tire Maker's Shares Sold                
The Cooper Tire and Rubber Company's largest shareholder, Shapiro Capital Management, reduced its stake in the tire maker by 73 percent in the third quarter. Shapiro Capital held 1.87 million shares in Cooper, or 3 percent of its shares outstanding, as of Sept. 30, according to a regulatory filing. That compared with 7.01 million shares, or 11 percent of the company, on May 31. Shapiro is now Cooper's 17th-largest shareholder. Shapiro Capital sold shares in the same period that Cooper announced a plan to add $170 million a year in profits by trimming spending and increasing revenue. The tire maker, which had a $9.36 million loss last year, is facing declining demand and higher costs for materials like rubber.










COMPANY NEWS

                    COOPER TIRE TO CUT JOBS AND QUIT MAKING INNER TUBES                
The Cooper Tire and Rubber Company said yesterday that it would cut 129 jobs at a factory in Mississippi and would stop producing inner tubes there because of declining demand. The cuts will result in $7 million of expenses in the third quarter, the company said in a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission. Cooper Tire, based in Findlay, Ohio, said it would dedicate resources to making other products that would help it expand. Thirty employees will continue working at the factory, in Clarksdale, Miss., the company said.










COMPANY NEWS

                    COOPER TIRE'S EARNINGS TO MISS ESTIMATES OF ANALYSTS                
The Cooper Tire and Rubber Company said it earned 13 cents to 17 cents a share in the second quarter, falling short of analysts' estimates because of higher raw material costs, slower sales and reorganization-related expenses. Analysts surveyed by Thomson First Call expected the company to earn 24 cents a share. Cooper Tire is due to release earnings July 17. The tire maker, based in Findlay, Ohio, closed four plants in the United States for a week in May because of a buildup of unsold tires. That cut 4 cents from earnings per share, while charges related to restructuring cost 2 cents a share, the company said.











                    Supreme Court Refuses to Hear Tire Appeal                
The United States Supreme Court refused today to hear an appeal from a tire maker of a $3.3 million jury award in the 1995 highway death of a Mississippi woman. The court refused to consider the argument by the tire maker, the Cooper Tire and Rubber Company, that the size of the award was so excessive that it violated the constitutional right to due process. The justices issued a one-line order without further comment.










COMPANY NEWS

                    COOPER TIRE SAYS IT WILL CUT 1,100 JOBS AND CLOSE PLANTS                
The Cooper Tire and Rubber Company said yesterday that it would eliminate 1,100 jobs, or 4.8 percent of its work force, and close, sell or consolidate 18 plants and offices to cut costs. Cooper will take a charge of $35 million to $40 million in the fourth quarter to cover the closings and job cuts. The announcement came as Cooper said third-quarter net income fell 32 percent, to $23.4 million, or 32 cents a share, from $34.6 million, or 45 cents, in the period last year. Sales rose 59 percent, to $843.6 million, from $531.9 million, primarily from its acquisition of the auto-parts maker Standard Products. The company will close plants immediately in Luzerne and Mio, Mich., and in Rocky Mount, N.C. It will also close the Oliver Rubber plant in Dallas.











                    Cooper Tire May Become Focus of a Safety Investigation                
Six weeks after it pressed Bridgestone/Firestone to recall 6.5 million tires, the nation's traffic safety agency said yesterday that it was considering opening an investigation of a second tire maker -- the Cooper Tire and Rubber Company. Dr. Sue Bailey, head of the agency, the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, said her office had recently become aware of lawsuits asserting that dozens of deaths and serious injuries had been caused by premature tread separations on tires made by Cooper, the world's fourth-largest tire maker.










COMPANY NEWS

                    COOPER TIRE AND RUBBER TO ACQUIRE STANDARD PRODUCTS                
The Cooper Tire and Rubber Company agreed yesterday to acquire the Standard Products Company for $36.50 a share in cash or stock, or a total of $584.4 million, in a deal that would make Cooper the largest maker of automotive sealing systems in North America. Cooper will also assume $173 million of Standard Products' debt. Cooper, based in Findlay, Ohio, said it expected revenue of $3.2 billion in the combined company's first full year of operation. Standard Products, based in Dearborn, Mich., makes sealing products, plastic trim and vibration control systems. Cooper is the nation's seventh-largest tire manufacturer. Shares of Standard Products soared 40 percent, rising $10, to $35, while Cooper fell 43.75 cents to $22.50.










COMPANY NEWS

                    PIRELLI AND COOPER TIRE COMPANIES FORM AN ALLIANCE                
Pirelli S.p.A., the world's sixth-largest maker of tires, said yesterday that it had formed an alliance with the Cooper Tire and Rubber Company, the eighth-largest, which the Italian company hopes will double its North American sales in three years. Cooper will distribute and sell Pirelli passenger and light-truck tires in North America, the world's largest market, which generates some 30 percent of Cooper's sales. In turn, Pirelli will market Cooper tires in the South American market, where it is one of the largest distributors.










